You said:
how can i share my website with my website to preview
ChatGPT said:

You want to share a live preview of your website with someone, right? There are a few ways to do it depending on whether your site is local (on your computer) or already deployed online. Let’s go step by step.

1. If your website is only on your computer (local server)

If you run it with npm start or yarn start, your site usually runs at http://localhost:3000. But localhost is only accessible on your own computer. To share it with someone else:

Option A: Use ngrok

  1. Install ngrok:

    bash
    npm install -g ngrok

  2. Run your local server (npm start).

  3. In a new terminal, run:

    bash
    ngrok http 3000

  4. Ngrok will give you a URL like https://abcd1234.ngrok.io.

    • Share this URL with anyone—they can preview your site live.

Option B: Use Localhost.run

  1. Run your server (npm start).

  2. Run:

    bash
    ssh -R 80:localhost:3000 ssh.localhost.run

  3. You get a URL to share with others.

2. If you want a free permanent URL (deploy online)

Option A: Netlify (Frontend only, React/Vue/HTML)

  1. Go to Netlify, sign up.

  2. Drag and drop your build folder (React: npm run build → build folder).

  3. Netlify gives you a live URL to share.

Option B: Render (Fullstack with backend)

  1. Go to Render, sign up.

  2. Connect your GitHub repo with the project.

  3. Render deploys both frontend and backend for free (with some limitations).

  4. You get a live URL to share.

Option C: Vercel (Frontend or Fullstack)

  1. Go to Vercel, sign up.

  2. Import your project from GitHub.

  3. Vercel gives you a live URL.

✅ Recommendation:

  • If you just want a quick share for testing, use ngrok.

  • If you want a permanent live site, use Netlify (frontend) or Render/Vercel (fullstack).

If you want, I can give you a simple step-by-step to deploy your React + Node.js site completely for free, including backend and frontend, so you can share it with anyone.

Step 2: Make sure the path is in your system PATH

  2. Click Environment Variables.

  3. Under User variables, find Path, select it, and click Edit.

  4. Add the folder from Step 1 (C:\Users\USER\AppData\Roaming\npm).

  5. Click OK and restart PowerShell.

Step 3: Test ngrok

powershell
ngrok --version

  • You should now see the version number.

Ah, I see! You want me to clarify exactly how to do those steps to get ngrok working on Windows. Here’s a simple guide:

Step 1: Add ngrok to your system PATH

  1. Press Win + S → type Environment Variables → select Edit the system environment variables.

  2. Click Environment Variables…

  3. Under User variables (or System variables), find Path → select it → click Edit.

  4. Click New and paste this folder:

makefile
C:\Users\USER\AppData\Roaming\npm

  1. Click OK on all windows to save.

  2. Restart PowerShell (important so it recognizes the new PATH).

Step 2: Test ngrok

Open a new PowerShell window and run:

powershell
ngrok --version

  • You should now see ngrok’s version number.

Step 3: Run your React app

In your project folder, run:

powershell
npm start

  • Your app will open at http://localhost:3000.

Step 4: Start ngrok to get a live URL

Open another terminal and run:

powershell
ngrok http 3000

  • You’ll see something like:

nginx
Forwarding   https://abcd1234.ngrok.io -> http://localhost:3000

  • Copy the https://abcd1234.ngrok.io URL. Anyone with this link can preview your website.
